\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 15. Key Design Decisions\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0
\cf0 15.1 Why CLI First?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Because the hard part is review quality, not UI.\
A CLI lets us validate the core loop quickly:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \
PR ingestion \uc0\u8594  context \u8594  agents \u8594  dedupe \u8594  judge \u8594  report\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 Once that works, GitHub Action and UI are wrappers.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 15.2 Why Multi-Agent?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Different agents catch different classes of issues.\
A general reviewer may catch logic bugs.\uc0\u8232 A test reviewer may catch missing coverage.\u8232 A repo pattern reviewer may catch inconsistency.\u8232 A security reviewer may catch permission problems.\
The value is not \'93more agents\'94.\uc0\u8232 The value is independent perspectives followed by strict filtering.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 15.3 Why LLM-as-a-Judge?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 The judge is useful for ranking and filtering, not for blindly deciding truth.\
The judge should not ask:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \
Is this issue true?\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 It should ask:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \
Is this issue evidence-backed, actionable, and likely to matter to a human reviewer?\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 15.4 Why Skeptic Before Judge?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Without a skeptic step, the judge may rank polished but unsupported findings.\
The skeptic step protects the system from confident false positives.\
Flow:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \
Agents generate candidates.\
Skeptic attacks candidates.\
Judge ranks survivors.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 15.5 Why Require Evidence?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Because developers will quickly stop trusting the tool if it produces vague comments.\
Bad finding:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \
This code may have edge cases.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 Good finding:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \
The new updateSettings handler mutates project settings before checking whether the user is a project admin. Existing deleteProject and inviteUser handlers both call requireProjectAdmin before mutation.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 16. Open Questions\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 These do not block the MVP.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \
Should the tool use GitHub MCP, GitHub REST API, gh CLI, or a hybrid?\
Should Codex and Claude be invoked via CLI, SDK, or internal wrapper?\
Should the first version support monorepos?\
Should review agents see the full repo or only curated context?\
Should fix mode apply patches automatically or only write patch.diff?\
Should eval mode compare against all human comments or only resolved review comments?\
Should team profile be global, per repo, or per team?\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 Recommended MVP answers:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \
Use GitHub REST API or gh CLI first.\
Support model adapters behind a common interface.\
Support monorepos only heuristically.\
Send curated context first, not the whole repo.\
Write patch.diff first; apply only with --apply.\
Eval only valuable human comments where possible.\
Team profile should be per repo initially.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 17. Final Recommended Build Order\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Use this exact order:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \
1. CLI + config\
2. PR ingestion\
3. Local workspace\
4. Review packet\
5. One reviewer\
6. Multiple reviewers\
7. Finding schema validation\
8. Deduplication\
9. Skeptic\
10. Judge\
11. Report\
12. Fix mode\
13. Eval mode\
14. Team profile\
15. Publish / GitHub Action\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 Do not start with:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 \
UI\
GitHub Action\
Inline PR comments\
Full auto-fix\
Complex multi-agent framework\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 Start with the core product loop.\
That is what will make the demo feel serious.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
